    <node id="claim:0001">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Splitting entity extraction and pseudonymisation into separate modules lets us apply discrete metrics and benchmarks that Kumulus's combined design cannot</data>
      <data key="d17">opinion</data>
      <data key="d18">False</data>
      <data key="d4">0.9</data>
      <data key="d5">[{"quote": "Rowan: they had like entity extraction and pseudonymization, like all kind of like baked into one thing. Whereas if we broke it up, we could actually apply discrete, discrete metrics and benchmarks", "ts": 145.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d6">["chapter:02"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0002">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">The medallion (bronze/silver/gold) pattern is too mature for the early POC; raw plus curated is enough</data>
      <data key="d17">opinion</data>
      <data key="d18">True</data>
      <data key="d19">Laura: maybe just having the output won't give us like enough information to be able to evaluate all of them (asks for an intermediate layer).</data>
      <data key="d4">0.9</data>
      <data key="d5">[{"quote": "Rowan: that's quite mature and for our implementation and early stages, we may probably only need two layers, like a raw and a curated set", "ts": 225.0, "source": "transcript"}, {"quote": "Laura: maybe just having the output won't give us like enough information to be able to evaluate all of them.", "ts": 290.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d6">["chapter:02"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0003">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Kumulus's stated ingestion success criterion ('one to two surgery cases processed') is not a real metric of ingestion quality</data>
      <data key="d17">opinion</data>
      <data key="d18">False</data>
      <data key="d4">0.9</data>
      <data key="d5">[{"quote": "Rowan: They said success criteria for ingestion was one to two surgery cases processed. Like that doesn't, that's not, there's no metrics there to say, well, was it ingested well?", "ts": 425.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d6">["chapter:03"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0004">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">ScoreBench is a tool that can be run; ExtractBench is a methodology where you prepare your own ground-truth data and measure against it</data>
      <data key="d17">fact</data>
      <data key="d18">False</data>
      <data key="d4">0.9</data>
      <data key="d5">[{"quote": "Rowan: that score bench is an actual tool that we could run. and extract bench is just a methodology. So we prepare our own graph, ground truth data and then measure it.", "ts": 450.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d6">["chapter:03"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0005">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Rule structuring (Cypher queries / graph DB setup) is novel and has no clear established benchmark we can use</data>
      <data key="d17">uncertain</data>
      <data key="d18">False</data>
      <data key="d4">0.9</data>
      <data key="d5">[{"quote": "Rowan: there's some things that just don't have metrics, like the rule structuring that's kind of novel really... there isn't really any, as far as I can tell, clear benchmarks that we can use for that.", "ts": 500.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d6">["chapter:03"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0006">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Rowan should nail down the metrics and benchmarks with Kumulus sooner rather than later if the engagement proceeds, so they know what is expected</data>
      <data key="d17">opinion</data>
      <data key="d18">False</data>
      <data key="d4">0.9</data>
      <data key="d5">[{"quote": "Rowan: if we go proceed with Cumulus, I would suggest that we try and nail down some of these things sooner rather than later so that they kind of know what we're expecting.", "ts": 470.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d6">["chapter:03"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0007">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Asking Kumulus to extract every possible entity could consume the entire budget; better to have them prove the foundation/structure and evolve it over time</data>
      <data key="d17">opinion</data>
      <data key="d18">False</data>
      <data key="d4">0.9</data>
      <data key="d5">[{"quote": "Rowan: if we were to ask Cumulus to like extract all of this, that could be like the entire budget to build out a system that goes super duper deep. And so maybe we just needed them to prove the foundation and the structure and it works and then we could evolve it over time.", "ts": 660.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d6">["chapter:04"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0008">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">The entity set must serve two purposes: pseudonymisation and graph representation</data>
      <data key="d17">opinion</data>
      <data key="d18">False</data>
      <data key="d4">0.9</data>
      <data key="d5">[{"quote": "Laura: the entities that we have to extract has to be like for two things. One is pseudonymization. That's one of the purposes. And then the other purpose is graph representation.", "ts": 740.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d6">["chapter:04"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0009">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">The entity model should be generalisable to natural and legal entities (per the patent), not just clinical cases</data>
      <data key="d17">opinion</data>
      <data key="d18">False</data>
      <data key="d4">0.9</data>
      <data key="d5">[{"quote": "Laura: remember in the patent it says like, if it's like a natural and legal entity... so I think that perhaps it makes sense to make it generalizable enough for non-clinical cases potentially.", "ts": 625.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d6">["chapter:04"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0010">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Address and location is a highly identifiable element and likely a high-value entity in the pseudonymisation context</data>
      <data key="d17">opinion</data>
      <data key="d18">False</data>
      <data key="d4">0.9</data>
      <data key="d5">[{"quote": "Deon: I'm just thinking about something like address and location... that sort of thing feels like a highly identifiable element for an entity. And that's probably a high, high value one in the pseudonymization context.", "ts": 705.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d6">["chapter:04"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0011">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Databricks is more composable and gives finer control over data staging; Fabric is a newer all-in-one abstraction layer</data>
      <data key="d17">opinion</data>
      <data key="d20">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d18">False</data>
      <data key="d4">0.9</data>
      <data key="d5">[{"quote": "Databricks is like the longer standing tool. They say Microsoft fabric is like this, the more recent one. And it's more of like a all baked in tool as opposed to Databricks, which is more you pick and like more composable", "ts": 905.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d6">["chapter:05"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0012">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Microsoft Fabric has only been around two to three years and was built to consolidate Microsoft's disparate data-processing tools into one</data>
      <data key="d17">assertion</data>
      <data key="d20">person:deon-kuhn</data>
      <data key="d18">False</data>
      <data key="d4">0.9</data>
      <data key="d5">[{"quote": "It's, it's only been around for two, about two or three years, maybe.", "ts": 935.0, "source": "transcript"}, {"quote": "the purpose was to consolidate all their disparate tools that they had for data processing and represented into one thing. So yeah, it's like a catch all for anything data related.", "ts": 955.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d6">["chapter:05"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0013">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">The proposed tools (Azure Data Factory connectors, Blob storage monitoring, AI Foundry for models) are the right choices</data>
      <data key="d17">opinion</data>
      <data key="d20">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d18">False</data>
      <data key="d4">0.9</data>
      <data key="d5">[{"quote": "the things that they suggest in terms of Azure data factory for like the connectors to get the data into Databricks, like is the absolutely the right thing. Blob storage monitor for checking ... AI foundry for the models.", "ts": 970.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d6">["chapter:05"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0014">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">CQRS separates the ingestion/processing layer from the queryable layer used by MedBrief; sensible for production scaling but not essential for a proof of value</data>
      <data key="d17">opinion</data>
      <data key="d20">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d18">False</data>
      <data key="d4">0.9</data>
      <data key="d5">[{"quote": "they separate the kind of ingestion and processing layer out from the kind of queryable layer for like when we use the data. ... makes sense from a like a scaling perspective when we actually bring it into production, but it's not an absolute necessary, I say for like a proof of value", "ts": 1040.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d6">["chapter:06"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0015">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Presidio is the leading first-pass pseudonymisation tool, combining regex plus LLMs and configurable with a human-in-the-loop, also usable as the production PII pipeline once configured</data>
      <data key="d17">opinion</data>
      <data key="d20">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d18">False</data>
      <data key="d4">0.9</data>
      <data key="d5">[{"quote": "the tool for doing like the, the first run seems to be like overwhelmingly a tool called Presidio", "ts": 1180.0, "source": "transcript"}, {"quote": "it allows you to combine like regex plus like LLMs and all of that kind of stuff. Like you can like configure it ... then you can also use it as like the proper pipe, like PII pipeline once you've configured it appropriately", "ts": 1260.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d6">["chapter:07"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0016">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Microsoft is trying to sell Presidio</data>
      <data key="d17">assertion</data>
      <data key="d20">person:laura-gongas</data>
      <data key="d18">False</data>
      <data key="d4">0.9</data>
      <data key="d5">[{"quote": "They, they've told us a lot about it. Microsoft is trying to sell it.", "ts": 1195.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d6">["chapter:07"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0017">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">spaCy is a traditional NER approach, good for an initial run or simple cases; other models perform better on complex ones</data>
      <data key="d17">opinion</data>
      <data key="d20">person:laura-gongas</data>
      <data key="d18">False</data>
      <data key="d4">0.9</data>
      <data key="d5">[{"quote": "Spacey, it's a, it's a very like traditional, approach for natural language tasks. ... it's normally good for an initial run, or for like quite simple cases. But, I know that other models, do perform better for more complex ones, but I think that for our initial run might work.", "ts": 1420.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d6">["chapter:07"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0018">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Entity extraction is handled in two steps: spaCy/NLP identifies entities, GLiNER classifies them / does relationships</data>
      <data key="d17">assertion</data>
      <data key="d20">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d18">False</data>
      <data key="d4">0.9</data>
      <data key="d5">[{"quote": "the entity extraction is kind of handled in two steps, right? There's like the natural language processing, which something like spacey is good for ... and then there's this other model, model called Galina, which I think does the relationships ... the spacey, like just identifies entities and then Galina would classify them.", "ts": 1305.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d6">["chapter:07"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0019">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Data-protection constraints apply to the NLP models used; some open-source models can be self-hosted (worthwhile for small NLP models)</data>
      <data key="d17">risk</data>
      <data key="d20">person:laura-gongas</data>
      <data key="d18">False</data>
      <data key="d4">0.9</data>
      <data key="d5">[{"quote": "we also have to be careful with the models that we use to make sure that, they meet with like protection of the data, et cetera, because some open source models.", "ts": 1465.0, "source": "transcript"}, {"quote": "There's normally always an option to self-host and for some models, it makes sense for others. It's just too expensive.", "ts": 1480.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d6">["chapter:07"]</data>
    </node>
