      <data key="d32">M1. Document ingestion &amp; OCR. This turns database information, raw case documents, including scanned and handwritten notes, into clean text. | Table: [blank] | Kumulus proposed | We propose | Inputs -&gt; outputs: In: raw PDFs, scanned images, Postgres structured records. Out: extracted text with layout and coordinates, per-document provenance, metadata (case ID, timestamps). | Same as Kumulus (we just need to check the details). | Metric: None really stated. They have set the target as '1-2 surgery cases of the same medical domain processed?' | Parse accuracy / content fidelity, completeness (recall of relevant passages), noise and error count given. | Benchmark: None stated. | SCORE-Bench? reference targets (fidelity above 0.883, hallucination under 0.036) and ExtractBench? methodology, measure against our own ground-truth data that we prepare (probably the 1 case?). | Implementation: Reuse the existing Azure Document Intelligence OCR; no re-OCR of handwritten notes from scratch (24 May). | Same as Kumulus. | Demo: Commodity; we already use Azure Document Intelligence, and it hits the benchmarks (I think?). | Summary: This looks like it is already in place, we just need to check if there is any further work to be done to adapt or expose it for Kumulus. We need to introduce some better metrics and consider some proper benchmarks. | M2. Natural Language semantic processing. Read the extracted text and work out the structure (who did what to whom): semantic role labelling, handling passive voice and synonyms etc., mapping plain wording to the patent's generalised forms. | Inputs -&gt; outputs:</data>
