      <data key="d5">[{"quote": "Rowan Kumulus Research\n\nNavigation\n\nOwner: Fluid.\n\nSummary: Kumulus don't discretely cover this in their proposal. But it would be good to split it out so it can be discretely measured. It looks like step1/2 is the best model to use for this step.\n\nM1: Entity extraction &amp; classification\nFind the things in the text and label what each one is, against our medico-legal list: patient, clinician, organisation, plus the clinical group (drug, dose, procedure, diagnosis, allergy).\n\nKumulus proposed | We propose\n\nInputs &amp; outputs: Text in, detected entities out (patient, doctor, location, event) (date step 3). | In: raw text with semantic roles. Out: labelled entity spans with [ID, IDT] types and the clinical group.\n\nMetric: Manual review. Laura pushed back and assured quantitative evaluation. | Precision, recall and F1 for spans; typing accuracy against the taxonomy; consistency.\n\nBenchmark: | We can run CoNLL-2003 (F1 above 0.90) and compare against a known SOTA. LegNER is a legal benchmark which we could adapt. We would need to build our own ground truth.\nRelated note: Sirion is a system that does entity classification on contracts that we could look at.\n\nImplementation: NLP + IE workstream. The devil's medusa suggested a built capability, but we should benchmark. Fluid Kumulus admitted no actual framework. | On Foundry, a general Azure OpenAI model prompted to pull the entities out (no fine tuning, in line with NER, GLINER, a small open-source extraction model, is a ...\n\n(right margin: language comprehension and include that in our tests. We could use the GPT model in Foundry. There is also an older or newer trained model called GliNER which we could test.)", "ts": 1308.3, "source": "vision"}]</data>
      <data key="d6">["chapter:07"]</data>
      <data key="d29">chapframe-07.png</data>
      <data key="d30">1308.3</data>
      <data key="d31">document</data>
      <data key="d32">Rowan Kumulus Research

Navigation

Owner: Fluid.

Summary: Kumulus don't discretely cover this in their proposal. But it would be good to split it out so it can be discretely measured. It looks like step1/2 is the best model to use for this step.

M1: Entity extraction &amp; classification
Find the things in the text and label what each one is, against our medico-legal list: patient, clinician, organisation, plus the clinical group (drug, dose, procedure, diagnosis, allergy).

Kumulus proposed | We propose

Inputs &amp; outputs: Text in, detected entities out (patient, doctor, location, event) (date step 3). | In: raw text with semantic roles. Out: labelled entity spans with [ID, IDT] types and the clinical group.

Metric: Manual review. Laura pushed back and assured quantitative evaluation. | Precision, recall and F1 for spans; typing accuracy against the taxonomy; consistency.

Benchmark: | We can run CoNLL-2003 (F1 above 0.90) and compare against a known SOTA. LegNER is a legal benchmark which we could adapt. We would need to build our own ground truth.
Related note: Sirion is a system that does entity classification on contracts that we could look at.

Implementation: NLP + IE workstream. The devil's medusa suggested a built capability, but we should benchmark. Fluid Kumulus admitted no actual framework. | On Foundry, a general Azure OpenAI model prompted to pull the entities out (no fine tuning, in line with NER, GLINER, a small open-source extraction model, is a ...

(right margin: language comprehension and include that in our tests. We could use the GPT model in Foundry. There is also an older or newer trained model called GliNER which we could test.)</data>
      <data key="d33" />
      <data key="d34">c9d1d8d9d9c1c1c8</data>
    </node>
